data.content:
Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead. This is more precise — it pins the exception to the exact call:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions thrown *anywhere* in the test (including setup), masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes it to the exact statement and fails if no exception is thrown. You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```
